=========================================================
POINTER TO CONST IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
A Pointer to Const is a pointer that cannot modify the data it points to,
but the pointer itself can point to another variable.

Syntax:

const int* ptr;

or

int const* ptr;

Both are EXACTLY the same.

Read Right to Left:

ptr is a pointer to const int.

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

const int* ptr = &x;

        +------+
x ----> |  10  |
        +------+

ptr ----> x

Pointer can change.
Data cannot be modified through ptr.

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 10;
    int y = 20;

    const int* ptr = &x;

    // *ptr = 100;   // ERROR

    ptr = &y;        // OK
}

=========================================================
WHAT IS ALLOWED?
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

const int* ptr = &x;

ptr = &y;      // OK

Reason:
Pointer is not const.

=========================================================
WHAT IS NOT ALLOWED?
=========================================================

int x = 10;

const int* ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;    // ERROR

Reason:
Data is const through this pointer.

=========================================================
MEMORY DIAGRAM
=========================================================

Initially:

ptr ----> x

After:

ptr = &y;

ptr ----> y

Pointer can point elsewhere.

=========================================================
IMPORTANT INTERVIEW POINT
=========================================================

"Pointer to Const" means:

You cannot modify the data THROUGH THIS POINTER.

It does NOT mean the original object is immutable.

Example:

int x = 10;

const int* ptr = &x;

x = 100;          // OK

cout << *ptr;     // 100

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

int x = 10;

const int* ptr = &x;

// *ptr = 50;   // ERROR

x = 50;           // OK

cout << *ptr;

Output:

50

=========================================================
POINTER TO CONST vs CONST POINTER
=========================================================

1. Pointer to Const

const int* ptr;

Meaning:
Data constant.
Pointer modifiable.

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Const Pointer

int* const ptr;

Meaning:
Data modifiable.
Pointer constant.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW TABLE
=========================================================

Declaration               Data      Pointer
------------------------------------------------
const int* ptr            No        Yes
int* const ptr            Yes       No
const int* const ptr      No        No

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 1
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

const int* ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;      // ERROR
ptr = &y;        // OK

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 2
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

int* const ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;      // OK
ptr = &y;        // ERROR

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 3
=========================================================

int x = 10;

const int* const ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;      // ERROR
ptr = nullptr;   // ERROR

=========================================================
WHY DO WE USE POINTER TO CONST?
=========================================================

1. Prevent accidental modification.
2. Improve API safety.
3. Pass large objects efficiently.
4. Support const correctness.

=========================================================
MOST COMMON USE
=========================================================

void print(const string* str)
{
    cout << *str;
}

Function guarantees:

String will not be modified.

